# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball5-pan-american-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] The **2022 Baseball5 World Cup** was the first edition of the Baseball5 World Cup, the mixed-gender Baseball5 (B5) world championship organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation (WBSC).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] It was held in Mexico City from 7 to 12 November 2022.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Cuba won the tournament, beating Japan in the final 2 matches to 0.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Chinese Taipei finished third defeating Venezuela 2 matches to 0 in the bronze medal game.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] 1There was no qualification event for WBSC Americas and WBSC Oceania.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Teams were selected by World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2022-baseball5-world-cup] 2In October 2022, WBSC chose Hong Kong to replace Australia.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The **2024 Baseball5 Pan American Championship** was the first edition of the Baseball5 Pan American Championship, a Baseball5 tournament organized by WBSC Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The championship was held from 27 to 30 June 2024, in the Domo Bolivariano in Barquisimeto, Venezuela and was contested between four national teams.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] Cuba went undefeated to win the tournament, finishing the opening round 6–0 and defeating Mexico in the championship game.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] Venezuela, that lost the semifinals against Mexico, claimed the bronze medal.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The three teams qualified for the 2024 Baseball5 World Cup in Hong Kong.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The **2024 Baseball5 World Cup** was the second edition of the Baseball5 World Cup, the mixed-gender Baseball5 (B5) world championship organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation (WBSC).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] It was held in Hong Kong from 7 to 12 October 2024.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The tournament was won by Cuba in their second straight Baseball5 World Cup title.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The Cuban team defeated Japan in the championship game, a replay of the 2022 final, 2 sets to 0 to finish the tournament undefeated with a 9–0 record.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] Cuban players Briandy Molina and Haila González received the Male MVP and Female MPV of the World Cup.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] France claimed the bronze after defeating Venezuela in the bronze medal game, 2 sets to 0.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The 2024 World Cup cost $12 million to host, with the Baseball Association of Hong Kong providing half of the funding.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The event has been given "M" Mark status (major sport event) by the Hong Kong government.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] The **Americas Challenge** was a curling challenge held by the World Curling Federation between teams in its Americas zone.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] The winner of the challenge qualified their country for the World Curling Championships, and in later years, the runner-up for the now defunct World Qualification Event.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] The challenge is not automatically held every year, and only takes place when a team in the Americas zone challenges the second-ranked Americas team in that year's World Curling Championship (or the first-ranked team if the second-ranked is hosting).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] The challenge merged with the Pacific-Asia Curling Championships to become the Pan Continental Curling Championships in 2022.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] The first challenge was held in 2009, with Brazil losing to the United States.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] Brazil again challenged and lost to the United States in 2010, 2015, and 2017.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] In January 2018, with the United States automatically qualifying as hosts of the 2018 World Men's Curling Championship, Brazil challenged and lost to Canada.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] The November 2018 challenge was the first to see more than two teams competing, with Guyana joining the challenge for the first time.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] In 2019, Mexico joined the challenge with Guyana not competing.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] United States would win again, going 4-0.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] A women's event has only been held twice, in 2017 and 2019.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] In 2017, Brazil challenged the United States but lost.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] Brazil's women's team challenged the United States in November 2018, but conceded to the United States to qualify for the World Qualification Event.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-challenge] In 2019, Mexico joined the challenge but the United States still won going 4-0.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The **Americas**, sometimes collectively called **America**, are a landmass comprising the totality of North America and South America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] When viewed as a single continent, the Americas are the second largest continent by area after Asia and the third largest continent by population.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Americas make up most of the land in Earth's Western Hemisphere and constitute the "New World", in contrast to the "Old World" of Afro-Eurasia.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Along with their associated islands, the Americas cover 8% of Earth's total surface area and 28.4% of its land area.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The topography is dominated by the American Cordillera, a long chain of mountains that runs the length of the west coast.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The flatter eastern side of the Americas is dominated by large river basins, such as the Amazon, St.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Lawrence River–Great Lakes, Mississippi, and La Plata basins.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Since the Americas extend 14,000 km (8,700 mi) from north to south, the climate and ecology vary widely, from the arctic tundra of Northern Canada, Greenland, and Alaska, to the tropical rainforests in Central America and South America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Humans first settled the Americas from Asia between 20,000 and 16,000 years ago.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] A second migration of Na-Dene speakers followed later from Asia.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The subsequent migration of the Inuit into the neoarctic c.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] 3500 BCE completed what is generally regarded as the settlement by the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Norse colonization of North America saw several settlements established in Greenland, and perhaps on the mainland, however, these were later abandoned.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Spanish presence involved the enslavement of large numbers of the indigenous population of the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Diseases introduced from Europe and West Africa devastated the indigenous peoples, and the European powers colonized the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Mass emigration from Europe, including large numbers of indentured servants, and importation of African slaves largely replaced the indigenous peoples in much of the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Decolonization of the Americas began with the American Revolution in the 1770s and largely ended with the Spanish–American War in the late 1890s.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Americas are home to more than a billion inhabitants, two-thirds of whom reside in the United States, Brazil, and Mexico.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The name "America" was first recorded in 1507.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] A world map created by Martin Waldseemüller was the earliest recorded use of the term.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The name was also used (together with the related term *Amerigen*) in the *Cosmographiae Introductio*, apparently written by Matthias Ringmann, in reference to South America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] It was applied to both North and South America by Gerardus Mercator in 1538.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] "America" derives from *Americus*, the Latin version of the Italian explorer Amerigo Vespucci's first name.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The feminine form *America* was originally used to refer to the newly discovered continent, which is why it was accorded with the feminine names of the other continents: Asia, Africa, and Europa.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Since the 1950s, however, North America and South America have generally been considered by English speakers as separate continents, and taken together are called *the Americas*, or more rarely *America*.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] When conceived as a unitary continent, the form is generally *the continent of America* in the singular.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] However, without a clarifying context, singular *America* in English commonly refers to the United States of America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The region was initially termed America or New India on the Mercator maps.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Speakers of English generally refer to the landmasses of North America and South America as *the Americas*, the *Western Hemisphere*, or the *New World*.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The adjective *American* may be used to indicate something pertaining to the Americas, but this term is primarily used in English to indicate something pertaining to the United States.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Some non-ambiguous alternatives exist, such as the adjective *Pan-American*, or *New Worlder* as a demonym for a resident of the closely related New World.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Use of *America* in the hemispherical sense is sometimes retained, or can occur when translated from other languages.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] For example, the Association of National Olympic Committees (ANOC) in Paris maintains a single continental association for "America", represented by one of the five Olympic rings.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Mencken said, "The Latin-Americans use Norteamericano in formal writing, but, save in Panama, prefer nicknames in colloquial speech." To avoid "American" one can use constructed terms in their languages derived from "United States" or even "North America".
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In Canada, its southern neighbor is often referred to as "the United States", "the U.S.A.", or (informally) "the States", while U.S. citizens are generally referred to as "Americans".
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Most Canadians resent being referred to as "Americans".
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In Spanish, *América* is a single continent composed of the subcontinents of *América del Sur* and *América del Norte*, the land bridge of *América Central*, and the islands of the *Antillas*.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] *Americano* or *americana* in Spanish refers to a person from *América* in a similar way that in which *europeo* or *europea* refers to a person from *Europa*.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The terms *sudamericano/a*, *centroamericano/a*, *antillano/a* and *norteamericano/a* can be used to more specifically refer to the location where a person may live.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Also, the term *norteamericano* (North American) may refer to a citizen of the United States, though in formal writing it is less common since it is used for the inhabitants of North America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In Portuguese, *América* is a single continent composed of *América do Sul* (South America), *América Central* (Central America) and *América do Norte* (North America).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] It can be ambiguous, as *América* can be used to refer to the United States of America, but is avoided in print and formal environments.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The demonym 'American' (americano) is commonly used in Portuguese to refer to people from the United States, although the terms 'norte-americano', 'estadounidense' or 'estadunidense' also formally exist and are preferred by those who wish to distinguish it from the continental demonym.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In French, the word *américain* may be used for things relating to the Americas; however, similar to English, it is most often used for things relating to the United States, with the term *états-unien* sometimes used for clarity.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] *Panaméricain* may be used as an adjective to refer to the Americas without ambiguity.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] French speakers may use the noun *Amérique* to refer to the whole landmass as one continent, or two continents, *Amérique du Nord* and *Amérique du Sud*.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In French, *Amérique* is seldom used to refer to the United States, leading to some ambiguity when it is.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Similar to English usage, *les Amériques* or *des Amériques* is used to refer unambiguously to the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In Dutch, the word *Amerika* mostly refers to the United States.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Although the United States is equally often referred to as *de Verenigde Staten* ("the United States") or *de VS* ("the US"), *Amerika* relatively rarely refers to the Americas, but it is the only commonly used Dutch word for the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] This often leads to ambiguity; and to stress that something concerns the Americas as a whole, Dutch uses a combination, namely *Noord- en Zuid-Amerika* (North and South America).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Latin America and Central America are generally referred to as *Latijns Amerika* and *Midden-Amerika* respectively.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The adjective *Amerikaans* is most often used for things or people relating to the United States.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] There are no alternative words to distinguish between things relating to the United States or to the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Dutch uses the local alternative for things relating to elsewhere in the Americas, such as *Argentijns* for Argentine, etc.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The term *Pre-Columbian* is used especially often in the context of the great indigenous civilizations of the Americas, such as those of Mesoamerica (Olmec, Toltec, Teotihuacano, Zapotec, Mixtec, Aztec, Maya) and the Andean civilizations (Inca, Moche, Chavín, Muisca, Cañari).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Many pre-Columbian civilizations established characteristics and hallmarks which included permanent or urban settlements, agriculture, civic and monumental architecture, and complex societal hierarchies.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Some of these civilizations had long faded by the time of the first permanent European arrivals (c. late 15th–early 16th centuries), and are known only through archeological investigations.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Others were contemporary with this period, and are also known from historical accounts of the time.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] A few, such as the Maya, had their own written records.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] However, most Europeans of the time viewed such texts as pagan, and much was destroyed in Christian pyres.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Only a few hidden documents remain today, leaving modern historians with glimpses of ancient culture and knowledge.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The first inhabitants migrated into the Americas from Asia.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Habitation sites are known in Alaska and Yukon from at least 20,000 years ago, with suggested ages of up to 40,000 years.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Beyond that, the specifics of the Paleo-Indian migration to and throughout the Americas, including the dates and routes traveled, are subject to ongoing research and discussion.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Widespread habitation of the Americas occurred after the Late Glacial Maximum, from 16,000 to 13,000 years ago.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The traditional theory has been that these early migrants moved into the Beringia land bridge between eastern Siberia and present-day Alaska about 40,000–17,000 years ago, when sea levels were significantly lowered during the Quaternary glaciation.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] These people are believed to have followed herds of now-extinct pleistocene megafauna along *ice-free corridors* that stretched between the Laurentide and Cordilleran ice sheets.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Another route proposed is that, either on foot or using primitive boats, they migrated down the Pacific coast to South America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Evidence of the latter would since have been covered by a sea level rise of hundreds of meters following the last ice age.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Both routes may have been taken, although the genetic evidences suggests a single founding population.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The micro-satellite diversity and distributions specific to South American Indigenous peoples indicates that certain populations have been isolated since the initial colonization of the region.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] A second migration occurred after the initial peopling of the Americas; Na Dene speakers, found predominantly in North American groups at varying genetic rates, with the highest frequency found among the Athabaskans at 42%, derive from this second wave.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Linguists and biologists have reached a similar conclusion based on analysis of Amerindian language groups and ABO blood group system distributions.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Then the people of the Arctic small tool tradition, a broad cultural entity that developed along the Alaska Peninsula, around Bristol Bay, and on the eastern shores of the Bering Strait c.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Arctic small tool tradition, a Paleo-Eskimo culture, branched off into two cultural variants, including the Pre-Dorset and the Independence traditions of Greenland.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The descendants of the Pre-Dorset cultural group, the Dorset culture, were displaced by the final migrants from the Bering sea coast line, the Thule people (the ancestors of modern Inuit), by 1000 CE.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Around the same time as the Inuit migrated into Greenland, Viking settlers began arriving in Greenland in 982 and Vinland shortly thereafter, establishing a settlement at L'Anse aux Meadows, near the northernmost tip of Newfoundland.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Although there had been previous trans-oceanic contact, large-scale European colonization of the Americas began with the first voyage of Christopher Columbus in 1492.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The first Spanish settlement in the Americas was La Isabela in northern Hispaniola.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] This town was abandoned shortly after in favor of Santo Domingo de Guzmán, founded in 1496, the oldest American city of European foundation.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] This was the base from which the Spanish monarchy administered its new colonies and their expansion.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Santo Domingo was subject to frequent raids by English and French pirates.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] On the continent, Panama City on the Pacific coast of Central America, founded on August 15, 1519, played an important role, being the base for the Spanish conquest of South America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Conquistador Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón established San Miguel de Guadalupe, the first European settlement in what is now the United States, on the Pee Dee River in South Carolina.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] During the first half of the 16th century, Spanish colonists conducted raids throughout the Caribbean Basin, bringing captives from Central America, northern South America, and Florida back to Hispaniola and other Spanish settlements.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] France, led by Jacques Cartier and Giovanni da Verrazzano, focused primarily on North America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] English explorations of the Americas were led by Giovanni Caboto and Sir Walter Raleigh.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Dutch in New Netherland confined their operations to Manhattan Island, Long Island, the Hudson River Valley, and what later became New Jersey.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The spread of new diseases brought by Europeans and African slaves killed many of the inhabitants of North America and South America, with a general population crash of Native Americans occurring in the mid-16th century, often well ahead of European contact.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] One of the most devastating diseases was smallpox.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] European immigrants were often part of state-sponsored attempts to found colonies in the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Migration continued as people moved to the Americas fleeing religious persecution or seeking economic opportunities.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Millions of individuals were forcibly transported to the Americas as slaves, prisoners or indentured servants.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Decolonization of the Americas began with the American Revolution and the Haitian Revolution in the late 1700s.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] This was followed by numerous Latin American wars of independence in the early 1800s.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Between 1811 and 1825, Paraguay, Argentina, Chile, Gran Colombia, the United Provinces of Central America, Mexico, Brazil, Peru, and Bolivia gained independence from Spain and Portugal in armed revolutions.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] After the Dominican Republic won independence from Haiti, it was re-annexed by Spain in 1861, but reclaimed its independence in 1865 at the conclusion of the Dominican Restoration War.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The last violent episode of decolonization was the Cuban War of Independence which became the Spanish–American War, which resulted in the independence of Cuba in 1898, and the transfer of sovereignty over Puerto Rico from Spain to the United States.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Peaceful decolonization began with the United States's purchase of Louisiana from France in 1803, Florida from Spain in 1819, Alaska from Russia in 1867, and the Danish West Indies from Denmark in 1916.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Canada became independent of the United Kingdom, starting with the Balfour Declaration of 1926 and the Statute of Westminster 1931 and ending with the patriation of the Canadian Constitution in 1982.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Dominion of Newfoundland similarly achieved independence under the Balfour Declaration and Statute of Westminster, but relinquished self-rule in 1934.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] It was subsequently confederated with Canada in 1949.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The remaining European colonies in the Caribbean began to achieve peaceful independence well after World War II.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Jamaica and Trinidad and Tobago became independent in 1962, and Guyana and Barbados both achieved independence in 1966.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In the 1970s, the Bahamas, Grenada, Dominica, St.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Vincent and the Grenadines all became independent of the United Kingdom, and Suriname became independent of the Netherlands.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Belize, Antigua and Barbuda, and Saint Kitts and Nevis achieved independence from the United Kingdom in the 1980s.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Americas make up most of the land in Earth's Western Hemisphere.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The northernmost point of the Americas is Kaffeklubben Island, which is the most northerly point of land on Earth.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The southernmost undisputed point is Águila Islet, although the Antarctic islands of Southern Thule are sometimes taken into account.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The mainland of the Americas is the world's longest north-to-south landmass.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The distance between its two polar extremities, Murchison Promontory on the Boothia Peninsula in northern Canada and Cape Froward in Chilean Patagonia, is roughly 14,000 km (8,700 mi).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The mainland's most westerly point is the end of the Seward Peninsula in Alaska; Attu Island, further off the Alaskan coast to the west, is considered the westernmost point of the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Ponta do Seixas in northeastern Brazil forms the easternmost extremity of the mainland, while Nordostrundingen, in Greenland, is the most easterly point of the continental shelf.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] South America broke off from the west of the supercontinent Gondwana about 135 million years ago, forming its own continent.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] About 15 million years ago, the collision of the Caribbean Plate and the Pacific Plate resulted in the emergence of a series of volcanoes along the border that created a number of islands.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The gaps in the archipelago of Central America filled in with material eroded off North America and South America, plus new land created by continued volcanism.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] By three million years ago, the continents of North America and South America were linked by the Isthmus of Panama, thereby forming the single landmass of the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Great American Interchange resulted in many species being spread across the Americas, such as the cougar, procyonids, porcupines, opossums, armadillos, and hummingbirds.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The geography of the western Americas is dominated by the American Cordillera, with the Andes running along the west coast of South America and the Rocky Mountains and other North American Cordillera ranges running along the western side of North America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The 2,300-kilometer-long (1,400 mi) Appalachian Mountains run along the east coast of North America from Alabama to Newfoundland.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] North of the Appalachians, the Arctic Cordillera runs along the eastern coast of Canada.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The largest mountain ranges are the Andes and Rocky Mountains.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Sierra Nevada and the Cascade Range reach similar altitudes as the Rocky Mountains, but are significantly smaller.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In North America, the greatest number of fourteeners are in the United States, and more specifically in the US state of Colorado.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The highest peaks of the Americas are located in the Andes, with Aconcagua of Argentina being the highest; in North America Denali (Mount McKinley) in the US state of Alaska is the tallest.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Between its coastal mountain ranges, North America has vast flat areas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Interior Plains spread over much of the continent, with low relief.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Canadian Shield covers almost 5 million km2 of North America and is generally quite flat.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Similarly, the north-east of South America is covered by the flat Amazon basin.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Brazilian Highlands on the east coast are fairly smooth but show some variations in landform, while farther south the Gran Chaco and Pampas are broad lowlands.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The climate of the Americas varies significantly from region to region.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Tropical rainforest climate occurs in the latitudes of the Amazon, American cloud forests, southeastern Florida and Darién Gap.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In the Rocky Mountains and Andes, dry and continental climates are observed.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Often the higher altitudes of these mountains are snow-capped.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Southeastern North America is well known for its occurrence of tornadoes and hurricanes, of which the vast majority of tornadoes occur in the United States' Tornado Alley, as well as in the southerly Dixie Alley in the North American late-winter and early spring seasons.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Often parts of the Caribbean are exposed to the violent effects of hurricanes.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] These weather systems are formed by the collision of dry, cool air from Canada and wet, warm air from the Atlantic.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] With coastal mountains and interior plains, the Americas have several large river basins that drain the continents.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The largest river basin in North America is that of the Mississippi, covering the second-largest watershed on the planet.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Mississippi–Missouri river system drains most of 31 states of the United States, most of the Great Plains, and large areas between the Rocky and Appalachian mountains.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Mississippi–Missouri is the fourth-longest river system and has the tenth-greatest discharge in the world.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In North America, to the east of the Appalachian Mountains, there are no major rivers but rather a series of rivers and streams that flow east with their terminus in the Atlantic Ocean, such as the Hudson, Saint John, and Savannah rivers.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] A similar instance arises with central Canadian rivers that drain into Hudson Bay; the largest being the Churchill River.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] On the west coast of North America, the main rivers are the Colorado, Columbia, Yukon, Fraser, and Sacramento rivers.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Colorado River drains much of the Southern Rockies and parts of the Basin and Range Province.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The river flows approximately 1,450 miles (2,330 km) into the Gulf of California, during which over time it has carved out natural phenomena such as the Grand Canyon and created phenomena such as the Salton Sea.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Columbia is a large river, 1,243 miles (2,000 km) long, in central western North America and is the most powerful river on the West Coast of the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In the far northwest of North America, the Yukon drains much of the Alaskan peninsula and flows 1,980 miles (3,190 km) from parts of Yukon and the Northwest Territory to the Pacific.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Draining to the Arctic Ocean of Canada, the Mackenzie River drains waters from the Arctic Great Lakes of Arctic Canada, as opposed to the St Lawrence River that drains the Great Lakes of southern Canada into the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The Mackenzie River is the largest in Canada and drains 1,805,200 km2 (697,000 mi2).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The largest river basin in South America is that of the Amazon, which has the highest volume flow of any river on Earth.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The second largest watershed of South America is that of the Paraná River, which covers about 2,582,074 km2 (996,944 mi2).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] North America and South America began to develop a shared population of flora and fauna about 2.5 million years ago, when continental drift brought the two continents into contact via the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Initially, the exchange of biota was roughly equal, with North American genera migrating into South America in about the same proportions as South American genera migrated into North America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] This exchange is known as the Great American Interchange.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The exchange became lopsided after roughly a million years, with the total spread of South American genera into North America far more limited in scope than the spread of North American genera into South America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In exports and imports, in 2020, the United States was the world's second largest exporter (US$1.64 trillion) and the largest importer (US$2.56 trillion).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Mexico was the tenth largest exporter and importer.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Canada was the twelfth largest exporter and importer.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Brazil was the 24th largest exporter and the 28th largest importer.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Chile was the 45th largest exporter and the 47th largest importer.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Argentina was the 46th largest exporter and the 52nd largest importer.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Colombia was the 54th largest exporter and the 51st largest importer; among others.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] The agriculture of the continent is very strong and varied.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Countries such as United States, Brazil, Canada, Mexico, and Argentina are among the largest agricultural producers on the planet.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In livestock, the Americas are major producers.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In industrial terms, the World Bank lists the top producing countries each year, based on the total value of production.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In the production of oil, the continent had 8 of the 30 largest world producers in 2020: United States (1st), Canada (4th), Brazil (8th), Mexico (14th), Colombia (20th), Venezuela (26th), Ecuador (27th), and Argentina (28th).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In the production of natural gas, the continent had 8 of the 32 largest world producers in 2015: United States (1st), Canada (5th), Argentina (18th), Trinidad and Tobago (20th), Mexico (21st), Venezuela (28th), Bolivia (31st), and Brazil (32nd).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In the production of coal, the continent had 5 of the 30 largest world producers in 2018: United States (3rd), Colombia (12th), Canada (13th), Mexico (24th), and Brazil (27th).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In the production of vehicles, the continent had 5 of the 30 largest world producers in 2019: United States (2nd), Mexico (7th), Brazil (9th), Canada (12th), and Argentina (28th).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] In the production of steel, the continent had 5 of the 31 largest world producers in 2019: United States (4th), Brazil (9th), Mexico (15th), Canada (18th), and Argentina (31st).
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p01] Haiti has the lowest GDP per capita in the Americas, although its economy was growing slightly as of 2016.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] A city proper is the locality with legally fixed boundaries and an administratively recognized urban status that is usually characterized by some form of local government.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] An urban area is characterized by higher population density and vast human features in comparison to areas surrounding it.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Urban areas may be cities, towns or conurbations, but the term is not commonly extended to rural settlements such as villages and hamlets.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Urban areas are created and further developed by the process of urbanization and do not include large swaths of rural land, as do metropolitan areas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] that is socio-economically connected to the urban core city, typically by employment ties through commuting, with the urban core city being the primary labor market.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] In accordance with these definitions, the three largest population centers in the Americas are: Mexico City, anchor to the largest metropolitan area in the Americas; New York City, anchor to the largest urban area in the Americas; and São Paulo, the largest city proper in the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] All three cities maintain Alpha classification and large scale influence.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] The population of the Americas is made up of the descendants of four large ethnic groups and their combinations.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Latin America is typically contrasted with Anglo-America, where English, a Germanic language, is prevalent, and which comprises Canada (with the exception of Francophone Canada rooted in Latin Europe [France]—see Quebec and Acadia) and the United States.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Both countries are located in North America, with cultures deriving predominantly from British and other Germanic roots.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] The transatlantic slave trade brought millions of Africans to the territories of the Americas under the colonial rule of European powers, especially South America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] In South America, Portugal played a significant role in the trafficking of enslaved Africans, with estimates suggesting that about 40% of all Africans forcibly brought to the Americas were taken to Brazil alone, to work primarily in sugar cane plantations, mining, and agricultural endeavors.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] In North America, the British Empire was heavily involved in the transatlantic slave trade, with the establishment of colonies such as Virginia, where enslaved Africans were primarily used as labor in tobacco plantations and later in other agricultural and domestic sectors.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] This system perpetuated for centuries, shaping the socio-economic landscape of all nations of the hemisphere.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] After the Haitian Revolution led by Jean-Jacques Dessalines, which started in 1791 and was the only successful slave revolt in history, the world's first black republic was established.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] It started with the massacre of the white population, between 3,000 and 5,000 white men and women of all ages were killed.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Oui, nous avons rendu à ces vrais cannibales guerre pour guerre, crimes pour crimes, outrages pour outrages.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Oui, j’ai sauvé mon pays, j’ai vengé l’Amérique.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Yes, I have saved my country – I have avenged America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Other faiths include Buddhism; Hinduism; Sikhism; Baháʼí Faith; a wide variety of indigenous religions, many of which can be categorized as animistic; new age religions and many African and African-derived religions.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Syncretic faiths can also be found throughout the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Various languages are spoken in the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Some are of European origin, others are spoken by indigenous peoples or are the mixture of various languages like the different creoles.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] The most widely spoken first language in the Americas is Spanish, followed by English and Portuguese.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] The dominant language of Latin America is Spanish, though the most populous nation in Latin America, Brazil, speaks Portuguese.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Small enclaves of French-, Dutch- and English-speaking regions also exist in Latin America, notably in French Guiana, Suriname, and Belize and Guyana respectively.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Haitian Creole is dominant in the nation of Haiti, where French is also spoken.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Native languages are more prominent in Latin America than in Anglo-America, with Nahuatl, Quechua, Aymara, and Guaraní as the most common.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Various other native languages are spoken with less frequency across both Anglo-America and Latin America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Creole languages other than Haitian Creole are also spoken in parts of Latin America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] The dominant language of Anglo-America is English.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] French is also official in Canada, where it is the predominant language in Quebec and an official language in New Brunswick along with English.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] It is also an important language in Louisiana, and in parts of New Hampshire, Maine, and Vermont.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Spanish has kept an ongoing presence in the Southwestern United States, which formed part of the Viceroyalty of New Spain, especially in California and New Mexico, where a distinct variety of Spanish spoken since the 17th century has survived.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] It has more recently become widely spoken in other parts of the United States because of heavy immigration from Latin America.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] High levels of immigration in general have brought great linguistic diversity to Anglo-America, with over 300 languages known to be spoken in the United States alone, but most languages are spoken only in small enclaves and by relatively small immigrant groups.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Most of the non-native languages have, to different degrees, evolved differently from the mother country, but are usually still mutually intelligible.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Some have combined, however, which has even resulted in completely new languages, such as Papiamento, which is a combination of Portuguese, Spanish, Dutch (representing the respective colonizers), native Arawak, various African languages, and, more recently English.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] The lingua franca Portuñol, a mixture of Portuguese and Spanish, is spoken in the border regions of Brazil and neighboring Spanish-speaking countries.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] More specifically, Riverense Portuñol is spoken by about 100,000 people in the border regions of Brazil and Uruguay.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Because of immigration, there are many communities where other languages are spoken from all parts of the world, especially in the United States, Brazil, Argentina, Canada, Chile, Costa Rica, and Uruguay—very important destinations for immigrants.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in the Americas, having spread through the hemisphere after the growth of US influence in the late 19th century.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] It overtook cricket, a fellow bat-and-ball sport spread by earlier British influence, in most places outside of the Commonwealth Caribbean.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Other American sports, such as basketball, have grown throughout the region over time.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] Football is perhaps the most popular and followed sport in the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] The North American region which also includes the Central and Caribbean national associations is overseen by the CONCACAF, while the South American region and its national teams are represented by the CONMEBOL.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-p02] The following is a list of multinational organizations in the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The **Americas Rugby Championship**, often informally called the **Americas' Six Nations**, was an annual international rugby tournament between six North and South American nations: Argentina, Brazil, Canada, Chile, the United States and Uruguay.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The original Americas Rugby Championship (organised by World Rugby) was inaugurated in 2009, when various combinations of national, regional and development teams from North and South America competed for the title.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] In 2015, it was announced that from 2016, the competition would reform under the guidance of the Americas Rugby Association and the respective unions, to provide the six national sides with additional rankings tests annually.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The updated format was based on the structure of the European Six Nations Championship, coinciding with each other in February and March of each year.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] Prior to this, the last competitive tournament to be held across the Sudamérica–RAN region had been the PARA Pan American Championship, which had ceased after its 2003 edition.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] World Rugby granted all matches with test match status, with caps awarded for every match, with the exception of those involving the Argentina XV side.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] Originally formed in 2009 by World Rugby (then known as the International Rugby Board) to replace the North America 4 Series, was created to give the newly formed Canadian regions more competitive matches against strong opposition from the second teams of the United States and Argentina.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The winner of the inaugural Canadian Rugby Championship, BC Bears, went on to compete on the international stage, playing the winner of the international semi-final match between USA Select XV and Argentina Jaguars.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The Argentina Jaguars defeated the BC Bears 35–11 in the final to capture the tournament's first title.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] In 2010, the tournament was cut from 6 to 4 teams, scrapping the Canadian Division part of the tournament to create a solely international based tournament for development sides.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The USA Select XV and Argentina Jaguars were joined by the second team from Tonga, and a Canada Selects side made up of the top players in the 2010 CRC season.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] Each team played each other once in a round-robin format, gaining 4 points for a win, with the team on the most points at the end winning the title.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The tournament returned in 2012, having not taken place in 2011 due to the 2011 Rugby World Cup.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The tournament kept the same format as 2010, however the national side of Uruguay joined the tournament replacing Tonga A, though in 2014, Uruguay sent their second team Charrúas XV.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] Argentina Jaguars went on to win every tournament between 2012 and 2014.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The tournament was not held in 2015 because of the 2015 Rugby World Cup.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] In 2016, the tournament was relaunched and expanded to six teams with the inclusion of Brazil and Chile.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] Unlike the previous single-site tournament featuring lesser sides, the new tournament was held in February and March, concurrently with the European Six Nations Championship.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] Like the European championship, teams played both home and away, whereas players from European clubs will be available.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] A second competition, the Americas Rugby Challenge or ARCh was confirmed in August 2018, to be played in August and September.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The inaugural competition took place at the Estadio Cincuentenario in Medellín, Colombia from August 24 to September 1.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The new competition brought together Rugby Americas North (RAN) and Sudamérica Rugby, following the example of the Americas Rugby Championship, The Americas Rugby Challenge is officially the 'B' competition for the ARC.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] As with the Americas Rugby Championship, the new Americas Rugby Challenge saw all competing countries playing against each other.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The first edition of the competition was a Four Nations tournament with Rugby Americas North and Sudamérica Rugby both having two representatives each.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The host nation of **Colombia** were joined by Sudamérica Rugby rivals **Paraguay**.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] **Guyana** and **Mexico** represented Rugby Americas North.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] Played annually, the format of the Championship was simple: each team played every other team once in a round-robin format, making for a total of 15 matches played across the tournament.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] For each win, a team picked up 4 points and 2 for a draw.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] The team with the most points at the end won the title.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/americas-rugby-championship] Unlike previous ARC, overseas based players were available for selection, while Argentina mainly selected provincial and domestic players that were not part of their Super Rugby Jaguares side.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] The **Baseball5 Pan American Championship** is the main Baseball5 tournament in the Americas, governed by WBSC Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] The top three teams qualify to the Baseball5 World Cup.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Mexico, a member of WBSC Americas, hosted the 2022 Baseball5 World Cup, the inaugural tournament of the Baseball5 World Cup.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Since there was no qualifying event for the Americas, Cuba and Venezuela were invited by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to join Mexico in the championship as the three teams representing the Americas.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] The inaugural Baseball5 Pan American Championship was contested from 27 to 30 June 2024 in the Domo Bolivariano in Barquisimeto, Venezuela with four teams taking part: hosts Venezuela, Cuba, Mexico and Puerto Rico, who made its international debut in Baseball5 competition.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Cuba won the 2024 Baseball5 Pan American Championship undefeated, with a 6–0 opening round record, and beating Mexico 2 sets to 0 in the final.
[src:baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Venezuela, that lost the semifinals against Mexico, was awarded the bronze medal.
